This paper deals with the analysis of Distributed Hash Tables (DHTs) under churn, which is a common problem in distributed systems. The paper uses a master-equation-based approach, which is a technique used in non-equilibrium statistical mechanics to describe steady-state or transient phenomena. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. Additionally, the paper uses simulations to verify theoretical predictions, which suggests that it may also belong to the Numerical Analysis (cs.NA) sub-category. The paper also discusses the implications of churn on the functioning of DHTs, which suggests that it may belong to the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category. The paper deals with the analysis of DHTs, which are data structures used in distributed systems, suggesting that it may also belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with the performance and consistency of lookups under churn, which suggests that it may also belong to the Performance (cs.PF) sub-category.
